title: #21XOXO
short_synopsis: A young woman drifts through a parallel digital world—searching for love by navigating speed dating, hipster culture, and post-net detachment. The woman’s adventure becomes increasingly surreal with each fleeting encounter and virtual connection.
default_editorial: Can the instant gratification of the internet satisfy IRL desires? Bringing together live-action rotoscopy and retro graphics in a pastel color palette, this heady short captures the false optimism, cynical narcissism, and ardent hedonism that buzz through online communication.

title: ...A Valparaíso
short_synopsis: A melancholic narrator begins a tour up the steep hills and across the sea of Valparaíso, a Chilean port city that was once a central stop around Cape Horn. Now, the glories of a cosmopolitan past are a faint memory—and the contrasts between poor and rich are immediately evident.
default_editorial: This collaboration between Joris Ivens and Chris Marker fascinates not just for its subject matter—daily life in the titular Chilean seaport city—but the traces of their distinct points-of-view. A fertile dynamic emerges from the realism of Ivens’ images and the fluid associations of Marker’s prose.

content_rating.label: caution
content_rating.description: Contains material that may not be suitable for children or young adults.

title: 2 or 3 Things I Know About Her
original_title: 2 ou 3 choses que je sais d'elle
short_synopsis: Juliette Janson, a housewife from the Paris suburbs, lives in a high-rise apartment with her husband and two children. As consumer culture in Paris booms, Juliette decides to start a part-time job as a sex worker to afford some of life’s little luxuries and escape suburbia.
default_editorial: The “her” is Paris, but it’s also everything: Only Godard could conjure the cosmos in a cup of coffee—which he does in this brilliant, candy-colored provocation. A landmark transition from the maestro’s jazzy genre deconstructions of the 60s to his gorgeous and inquisitive essay films of the future.

short_synopsis: Images of cherry blossoms, luminous fields bursting with color, and miscellaneous domestic ephemera are photographed from the screen of an obsolete televisual device.
default_editorial: In Blake Williams’s impressionistic short, a flickering monitor provides an enigmatic visual commons in which intriguing footage of domesticity and the great outdoors wordlessly converge. Through inventive use of 3D technology, the fragility and malleability of the image becomes strikingly palpable.

short_synopsis: Chow Mo-Wan was a writer. He thought he wrote about the future but it really was the past. In his novel, a mysterious train left for 2046 every once in a while. Everyone who went there had the same intention: to recapture their lost memories. It was said that in 2046, nothing ever changed.
default_editorial: Forming a loose trilogy with Days of Being Wild and In the Mood for Love, Wong Kar Wai’s series of romantic dramas culminates in this sweeping, time-traveling epic. A film of ravishing visual grandeur and incredible ambition, 2046 offers a wistfully bittersweet look at love and loneliness.
